She is spayed and microchipped and has age-appropriate vaccinations. A licensing/microchip fee may apply. To meet Nala or to be added to her waitlist, call (505) 983-4309 x 1610 and leave a voicemail message that includes the DOG'S NAME, plus YOUR NAME and A GOOD PHONE NUMBER - OR e-mail this information to adoption@sfhumanesociety.org. A scheduler will call you back within 48 hours to confirm your request. If you have other dogs at home, tell the scheduler you would like to bring them along for a Meet n' Greet. SFAS offers a variety of excellent training classes, seminars and Trainer Talks led by animal behavior professionals. These are $50 off for animals adopted from any shelter or rescue group! Due to current COVID-19 restrictions, classes and talks are all presented virtually using Zoom. For course descriptions, schedules and registration, visit https://sfhumanesociety.org/our-programs/behavior-training/group-training-classes/ for classes and https://sfhumanesociety.org/our-programs/behavior-training/special-seminars-and-workshops/ for seminars and Trainer Talks.

animal.description:
Meet Jemma!

ATTENTION: PLEASE READ THROUGH TO SEE WHETHER YOU MEET OUR ADOPTION CRITERIA BEFORE RESPONDING. IF YOU MEET OUR CRITERIA FOR ADOPTION OF THIS DOG, PLEASE FOLLOW THE LINK TOWARD THE BOTTOM OF THE PROFILE TO COMPLETE OUR APPLICATION. THANK YOU!

This sweet little one is estimated to be about 3 years old. She weighs 7.5lbs. 

We don’t know what happened to Jemma, but she came in to the county shelter with visible scars on her head and some damage to one eye. Luckily, the injuries did not affect her vision, but the trauma has made her a bit sensitive. She is scared when meeting any new person, but once she loves and trusts, Jemma loves her person intensely. 

Jemma should not go to a home with cats or kids because she is afraid of them, but she absolutely must have a small dog companion who is under 8 years old in the home. This is what gives her confidence. Jemma can't live in an apartment or condo because the way she greets her person is with a very high pitched shrieking sound. Something neighbors will not likely appreciate. She's a sensitive little girl and would do best with a quiet home. Low stress is her ideal life (ours too!)


Adoption Process: We are not first come first served. Indigo Rescue focuses on finding good matches between dogs and families to ensure life long adoptions. We deliver all dogs to their new homes. All of our dogs are in foster homes. 

If you’re interested in meeting one of our dogs, please use the following link and complete our Adoption Application. You can either scan your completed application and email it to us at: info@indigorescue.org, or you can fax it to us at: 888-502-7660.
The link is not live, so you will need to copy and paste it into your browser: https://storage.googleapis.com/gator-users/user-680788/documents/d1742bff02e44c2ea25649cb45df5103/Pet%20Application%20Form%20December%202020.pdf
If the dog you're interested in seems compatible with your lifestyle we'll set up a time for you to meet the dog privately.
PLEASE NOTE: Indigo Rescue only adopts to homes within 30 miles of Beaverton because our volunteers deliver all of our dogs to their adoptive homes. We work very hard to create a family of our Indigo Rescue adopters because we want to be close enough to help in case there are any problems. We want everyone to be happy and successful!

**ALL of our dogs and puppies come vaccined to their age, spayed/neutered and microchipped.

Thank you for your interest in adopting and saving a life.

If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for one of our great dogs, please go to our website- www.luckymuttsrescue.org and submit an application. Our application process includes landlord approval and vet checks. Please make sure all of your information is current and accurate, including a valid email address and phone numbers. Inaccuracies and/or incomplete data will delay and/or cancel your application.  We strive to process all applications in a timely manner, but with the high volume of applications we are receiving, it is taking anywhere from 1-3 weeks.  You may be contacted via email if there are concerns or questions.  Once all of your information is reviewed and if your application is approved, you will be notified via email.  Submitting an application and receiving an approval does not guarantee you will be adopting the dog you applied for.  Once you move to the meet and greet process, you will be contacted by the foster family to further discuss the dog, and answer questions you may have, and if applicable, a meet and greet will be set up at our adoption center.   Meet and greets are only set up with approved applicants, and we require all members in the household to be present, as well as any current dogs in the home. 

Current Adoption Fees Are:
$400+tax for puppies to 3 years old
$350+tax for ages 4-7
$250+tax for ages 8 and up
Bonded pairs vary

The adoption fee covers spay/neuter, up to date age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, general deworming, heartworm test, (if over 6  months) and a certified veterinary inspection. Please be aware, listed dog breeds are based on information provided and cannot be guaranteed.  Submitting an application for a particular dog does not guarantee that you will be the applicant chosen, we receive several applications for each dog. Our adopters are picked based on the needs of the dog, and the home we feel with best fit based on your responses to our application, vet information and landlord requirements.   Approved applicants not chosen for the dog you applied for, will be in active status for a period of six months.  We encourage you to watch Petfinder, Facebook and our website for upcoming dogs.  Should you see a dog that interests you, please send us a Facebook message or an email with your approval number.  Please be patient with us, as Lucky Mutts Rescue is run strictly by volunteers and many of us work full time jobs, have families and also foster dogs. Thank you for considering Lucky Mutts Rescue for your next furry family member!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Hi, my name is Monty and my estimated DOB is 12/2018. I have finished my heart worm treatment and am now ready to go to my forever home! I'm from the south but have adjusted to the cold and snow nicely. My favorite things to do are sniffing you and have you hold my paw. I'm a really good dog and just want to please my people. I'm a very good listener and am really smart so I pick up things very quickly. I'm quiet and don't bark much at all. Though I will sometimes bark when I see dogs on our walks, but we are working on that. I love to walk so I can sniff, sniff, sniff. I also have been running with my foster mom which I'm getting better at. I'm just a real chill dog.

One thing I'm working extra hard on is my separation anxiety while you are away, I don't like being left alone and will bark. So I need a family that is patient with me as I settle in and will continue to work with me on this. I will not be able to live in a home where there are shared wells, such as an apartment or town home. I would also need a home where I wasn't left alone too often and in the instances where I am left, I need a nice sturdy crate, such as a no break kennel or an Alkatraz kennel, as I've been known to escape. I do like my crate when I can see you and that is where I keep my toys and where I get all my special bones and treats. I can't wait to sniff/meet you.
Interested in adopting this lovable animal? Please go to our website www.wagsmn.org and fill out an Adoption Application. Once the application is processed, a Wags representative will contact you, answer any questions you may have, and set up a time/location for a meet and greet! A home visit is required prior to adoption.

Thank you for choosing to adopt!

Breed and temperament determination: Wags & Whiskers Animal Rescue attempts to determine breed and temperament using a combination of looks, information provided to us at intake, and our experience with the animal while in our Rescue. We do not guarantee this determination.

animal.description: Bryson and Malik are brothers.  They are purebred Salukis that were saved from the desert in Bahrain where they were left because they weren't racers.  They are about 9 months old and weigh about 45 pounds.  They are neutered, up to date on their shots, healthy and happy.  They are bonded and need to be adopted together.  They are calm and polite and well behaved dogs.  They are fully house trained and love to run around the foster's yard.  They enjoy their walks and don't pull on the leash unless they spot a squirrel.  They hang out on the sofa or dog beds and enjoy being part of a family.  Preference will be to folks with sighthound experience and a fenced in yard.  Any children in the home need to be over age 8.  Salukis make wonderful companions and are just so expressive and happy and loyal.  If you live in the Toronto area and would like to meet them and learn about our foster to adopt program, please email our rescue at c4ptoronto@gmail.com.   Another video of them can be found at https://youtu.be/j4AgV_lmT-g.

I love stuffies a little too much, I like to get the squeaker out of it. I am very interested in what you have to say, I tilt my head and try to understand what you are saying, I'm very eager to learn new things. I'd do better in a home with kids that are around 7 or older, the little ones make me a bit nervous. I like other dogs and I'd need to meet any other dogs that are in the home before I can leave. I walk well on a leash and I do know sit. I do not do well with cats or livestock. I'm just an all around happy go lucky guy. If you are looking for a guy like me come on in and meet me so we can get going!

animal.description: Hi there, my name is Scooby, aka Scoobers, Scoober Doos! You could call me just about anything, just make sure you are ready for me to come running, because I love attention, like...all the time! I love toys, especially squeakie ones, but I can't have those because I like to eat them and they get stuck in my stomach. The Doc says I can't have them at all anymore. I can however have all the Kong toys I want. I play nice with those and I even give them back so you can throw them again. Can I be your only love? I'm pretty selfish when it comes to my people and don't like others getting in the way. If you think I would be the perfect fit for your home, please come in and meet me.

animal.description:
Bubbie has had a rough couple of months.  In early November he was turned in because he was not allowed at the apartment complex.  Several weeks later his original owner (who did not know he was turned in) came and took him back.  Bubbie then started peeing in the home and the family did not want to deal with this so they turned him in.  Then they decided to give him another chance, well that didn't work and they gave up on him and brought him back.
He is super confused and is looking for a committed FUREVER home!  Bubbie is an Australian shepherd blue heeler mix, and is birthday is 12/01/19.
If you are interested in meeting him please call the shelter (520) 458-4151 to schedule an appointment.

Booby is a 1 1/2 years old and weighs about 45 pounds.

Bobby is an active, fun, bouncy dog. He loves his family, and playing with other dogs. When he's not playing he loves to cuddle up to his human on the couch. He's done well sharing his toys and no negative behaviors with his food. Bobby is an energetic dog, he does well with other energetic dogs and would do best with a job. He'd be great for agility, or flyball competitions. He does need some work on the leash. Bobby's foster says he's a fun, happy, life-loving dog. Here's a bit more about Bobby. walks on a leash- slightly pulls and needs work dog friendly no cats crate trained house trained knows sit and will work for treats Protective of his home cuddle/kisses giver

 

Bobby is located in TX but is available to travel to the PNW when he finds his forever home. 

 

If you have an application on file please email Michelle at mmvolunteer15@gmail.com if not please fill out an application below for and interview. 

https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/19765/generic

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Gracie is a very active and energetic 1 year-old Lab/Border Collie mix who loves nothing more than tennis balls and playing fetch! You'd be hard-pressed to find a dog who's more into that than this friendly girl. She was an owner surrender at an overcrowded county dog shelter because her family was moving and couldn't take her along. Gracie certainly isn't letting the fact that she's looking for a new home get her down. She made the trip to Canine Lifeline so she could enjoy life in a foster home while searching for that new home and continues to have fun wherever she goes. Gracie gets along well with other dogs but doesn't necessarily need to have a canine buddy in her new home as long as she has tennis balls and someone to throw them for her. She would love having a yard with an aboveground fence so she could safely chase the ball to her heart's content. Gracie is quite strong on a leash so is going to need work on her leash manners. She does better with a harness so that's recommended as she works on her leash skills. Gracie has done well with crate-training in her foster home and may be housetrained too although we can't guarantee it. She is very food-motivated and can catch treats on the fly like a pro. She will also sit on command and eager to learn lots more with her new family. If you've got a great throwing arm and are looking for an active young dog who loves to have fun, Gracie just might be your girl! Gracie weighs about 50 pounds and her adoption fee is $350. She's spayed, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Gracie. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Gracie and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
Dottie is an absolute gem with the world’s best pittie smile. She is such a sweet girl and loves to give kisses and being around her people and fur friends. Her foster mom works from home and loves when Dottie wanders over every so often for pets and snuggle time. Dottie will often lay nearby and doze off during the day to keep a close eye on things. She makes sure she knows if her people start moving around. She is very curious about what everyone is doing, but just watches with interest instead of wanting to help too much. 

Dottie is currently kenneled at night and any other time she is going to be alone for an extended period of time. She had quite the adjustment to kennel time when first brought into rescue, but it only took a few days for her to get settled in and know that was a safe and comfy place to be. She wasn’t an escape artist. She didn’t bark for hours on end. Instead, she had such a long, woeful howl for 20 minutes or so after being kenneled up. From the other room, she sounded like Dory from “Finding Nemo” talking to the whale. Her foster family is actually kind of sad that she quit doing that because it was really funny to listen to. The human kids would try to guess what she was saying. 

Dottie has a nylabone in her kennel with her at night that she will occasionally chew on, but her favorite thing is her red, spiky ball. She carries it around with her all day long. She is even nice enough to let her foster siblings play with it. Her foster mom has kept a close eye on toy interactions, and Dottie doesn’t appear to resource guard her toy- which is amazing because it is her absolute favorite thing ever! She is also pleasant with food and doesn’t show any guarding of that either. Her foster family feeds everyone separately to avoid any issues, but her foster mom can take her bowl away halfway through and take toys away without problems.

Dottie has 5 foster fur siblings, and she has done very well adapting to her foster home life with very slow introductions. She does like to play, and at first, was a little too rowdy in the house with her fur friends. Now that she has been in her foster home a little while, she understands the rules a bit better and keeps the playing under control. 

As with all rescues, training is going to be an important piece of Dottie’s future. Her foster mom has been working on leash manners and basic obedience. Dottie is a smart cookie and has figured out not to pull her foster mom around the yard during potty breaks and is working really, really hard on her stay. She is eager to please and will often go back and forth from sit to lay down when in a stay waiting for her breakfast and dinner. She hasn’t quite figured out that it’s the stay that gets her the food, not her up and down shenanigans, but she’ll get there. 

Dottie is such a gentle and kind soul and loves to give little humans kisses without trampling them over in excitement. She would make an excellent family dog and would be happy with anyone that showed her lots of love. Her amazing personality and smile hopefully means she will find a family to adopt her very soon. Anyone would be lucky to have her!

To apply for adoption, please visit: www.4pitssakerescue.com

animal.description:
If you are looking for a real ""ham"" look no farther than adorable Eleanor Honey Ham! 

What can we say about Ms. Eleanor Honey Ham... She is incredibly affectionate and will certainly bond with her family pretty quickly. She is working on general manners such as gentle with treats and play, off (specifically the counter even though she's pretty low to the ground), getting into her crate on command and she can be a bit excitable. She gets nippy when she is excited and we are working hard on her with that. She showed some signs of possible food/possession aggression the first couple of days she was here but has been working very hard with ""sit, stay, ok."" 

She will need a family that is committed to continuing to work with her daily on this skill and basic obedience skills.She needs some work on leash training as well! You definitely need to keep your eye on her because if she isn't trying to cuddle you or following you around at your heels she's probably getting into trouble. She's really just a big puppy that doesn't know her own strength. 

We believe that an ideal home for her would be one that had either grown children or a single couple/person and most likely not someone that isn't stable with balance. She is goofy and super strong so she could easily bowl someone over and she's a ""coming in hot!"" kinda girl for the spot on the couch. She seems like she will take a bit of time to really settle so she'll need patience and love. We believe she would do best as an only dog and needs a family that fully understands and has experience with bully breeds like Eleanor. 


Name: Eleanor Honey Ham
Breed: American Staffordshire Terrier mix
Sex: Female
Age: 4 years old
Weight: 51 pounds
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Vaccinations: Up to date
Heartworm: Positive 
Microchipped: Yes

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS: 
Good with Children: Older children only.
Good with Dogs: Has fostered with other dogs with very slow introductions. We are recommending that she is an only dog. 
Good with Cats: Unknown

Adoption Fee: $475.00


IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.

Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.

At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.


NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

He still needs to be muzzled when meeting new people, but he does not have issues meeeting and playing with well-behaved dogs. Kobe is very comfortable with his muzzle and will allow you to put it on and will keep it on without any problem. He is comfortable in a crate. Kobe is a very smart boy and is working on new commands every day. He definitely as 'sit' and 'stay' and 'come' mastered. Kobe would do best in a home with no young children, a home that can give him a calm setting, and a household without a lot of people/strangers comeing in and out. We are hoping Kobe will mature and outgrow this one issue of being so nervous and fearful around new people but that remains to be seen._______________________________________________________Kobe came into rescue with reactivity towards both people and dogs He has been in specialized care and training at a facility to help him overcome his fear that is causing him anxiety and reactivity in certain environments. Kobe has made a lot of progress but will need continue support and training in his adoptive home. He will need someone experienced with the boxer breed and behaviors, as well as patience in introducing him to new people, dogs, and overall life experiences. He is a gorgeous boy that deserves the best life has to offer him at whatever level that may be. Kobe is a work in progress and each week he learns something new. Kobe was never socialized properly as a puppy and is working hard to overcome his issues. If you are interested in finding out more about Kobe and think you could offer him a safe and happy home, please contact us. We will be very picky about the home he goes to so he can grow into a well-socialized and happy adult.

animal.description:
My name is Luna I am about a year old and I am a Pit Bull Terrier mix. I can be a tad wary of strangers at first but I warm up to people pretty quickly! I am a medium energy girl who enjoys playing fetch but I am really just a big lap dog! I love to get some good scratches and I give great kisses! I seem to do well with other large dogs that are clearly submissive to me but I will need a home with no cats, chickens, or any other small animals. I would love a home with a secure yard for me to hangout in!

*Please Note, If you have other dogs or children living in the home, you will need to bring them down to meet at the shelter before the adoption process continues.

For more information please call the Humane Society of Cowlitz County at 360-577-0151 and ask to speak with a staff member. Calling from outside the Longview, Washington area? Use our toll-free line 866-310-9665. If you see a specific dog you are interested in please call to see if that pet is still available. We can also be reached by email at frontdesk@cowlitzhumane.com

animal.description: I love hanging out with People – I’m a little more selective with my doggie friends, especially when they are all vying for attention by barking, jumping, whining – you know the type.  And those little snappy dogs just don’t appeal to me much.  I have made a couple of good dog friends at the Shelter, although I prefer humans.   I really didn’t want to come here but now I’ve met all kinds of cool folks and I just know one of them is going to take me to my forever home.  I sure hope the one who picks me has a great big comfy sofa as I seem to be what some call a “couch potato”.  Take me home with you and let me curl up with you while you read a good book and I just enjoy your warmth and love.

Hi, my name is  Aspen.I am a 2 year old, 35# border collie mix.I am cute, sweet and loving.I am house broken and sleep in my crate.I do not pull on a leash because I am looking at what is around me..My foster mom says I am observant.I came from Oklahoma on the 17th and love the snow.I love humans and other dogs so much that I tend to cry when one leaves...please know I was previously fostered in a home with 8 other dogs so would love a family with another dog.I play well with the LMR alum who comes to spend the day at my foster home.Hoping to meet my forever family soon.

If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for one of our great dogs, please go to our website- www.luckymuttsrescue.org and submit an application. Our application process includes landlord approval and vet checks. Please make sure all of your information is current and accurate, including a valid email address and phone numbers. Inaccuracies and/or incomplete data will delay and/or cancel your application.  We strive to process all applications in a timely manner, but with the high volume of applications we are receiving, it is taking anywhere from 1-3 weeks.  You may be contacted via email if there are concerns or questions.  Once all of your information is reviewed and if your application is approved, you will be notified via email.  Submitting an application and receiving an approval does not guarantee you will be adopting the dog you applied for.  Once you move to the meet and greet process, you will be contacted by the foster family to further discuss the dog, and answer questions you may have, and if applicable, a meet and greet will be set up at our adoption center.   Meet and greets are only set up with approved applicants, and we require all members in the household to be present, as well as any current dogs in the home. 

Current Adoption Fees Are:
$400+tax for puppies to 3 years old
$350+tax for ages 4-7
$250+tax for ages 8 and up
Bonded pairs vary

The adoption fee covers spay/neuter, up to date age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, general deworming, heartworm test, (if over 6  months) and a certified veterinary inspection. Please be aware, listed dog breeds are based on information provided and cannot be guaranteed.  Submitting an application for a particular dog does not guarantee that you will be the applicant chosen, we receive several applications for each dog. Our adopters are picked based on the needs of the dog, and the home we feel with best fit based on your responses to our application, vet information and landlord requirements.   Approved applicants not chosen for the dog you applied for, will be in active status for a period of six months.  We encourage you to watch Petfinder, Facebook and our website for upcoming dogs.  Should you see a dog that interests you, please send us a Facebook message or an email with your approval number.  Please be patient with us, as Lucky Mutts Rescue is run strictly by volunteers and many of us work full time jobs, have families and also foster dogs. Thank you for considering Lucky Mutts Rescue for your next furry family member!

animal.description:
Please contact JoEllen (sagdinfo@aol.com) for more information about this pet.Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **
Caramelo is a handsome 3-year-old Labrador Retriever blend who weighs approximately 33 pounds. Caramelo was found as a stray in a small town in Mexico where he faced a sad life of starvation and abuse. A Good Samaritan in that area stepped in to change his fate and contacted our rescue for assistance. Caramelo initially is shy but once your offer him treats, he quickly displays his affectionate and loyal nature. Additionally, he will require leash training.
Please understand you are committing to providing a good home for his entire life (up to 15+ years or more.)
You must be committed to housebreaking, age-appropriate enrichment and exercise, leash training, grooming needs, and positive socialization.
His adoption fee is $175. This includes his neuter surgery, rabies vaccination, Nobivac Canine 1-DAPP vaccination, Nobivac Intra-Trac 3 vaccination, Drontal Plus, IDEXX SNAP 4Dx Plus Test, Tri-Heart Plus chewable tablet, 24PetWatch microchip, leash and collar, and a trial offer for 24PetWatch Pet Insurance.
Please be aware that puppies and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so interested parties are encouraged to apply online at www.saspca.org.
Please ensure your application is complete before submitting. We do verify property ownership, landlord references, apartment/HOA restrictions, veterinary references, and criminal histories.
Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio TX 78232. Event hours are 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m.
Additional questions may be directed to sagdinfo@gmail.com.
** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **

- IMPORTANT INFORMATION -

SASPCA Homeward Bound Dog Rescue and San Antonio Great Dane Rescue are 501(c)(3) foster-based rescue groups based in San Antonio, Texas.

Our group focuses on assisting open admission shelters in South Texas where over 32,000 dogs and cats are euthanized each year.

Our puppies and dogs are completely vetted and live in foster homes. They are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and tested for heartworm disease.All adoptions include one month of flea and heartworm preventative, leash and collar, and opportunity to enroll in a 30-day trial of pet insurance.

Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio, TX 78232. Event hours are typically 11:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

We also host additional adoption events throughout the year. Please visit our Facebook pages for the most current event schedules.

https://m.facebook.com/HomewardBoundDogRescue/?tsid=0.11494693985281179&source=typeahead

https://m.facebook.com/profile.php?id=185497084826453&tsid=0.7626298417270982&source=typeahead

If your adoption application is approved and you are traveling from out-of-town, we hold your chosen pet for one hour past the event start time to allow for travel time.

We are an all-volunteer organization and do not currently have the resources to process out-of-state adoptions.

Our puppies, purebred dogs, and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so we encourage interested parties to apply online.

Please apply here:

http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Hello everybody!  My name is Hooch! My foster family calls me Hutch.  I joined my foster family on January 18th.  I am a hound mix who is 3 years old and 54 pounds.  I am a quiet, milder dog who needs an extra moment to get used to new people.  Being from Oklahoma, I am learning about what city life is like with all of the loud and scary sounds.  At night, I sleep quietly in my crate.

Each day I warm up more and more to my foster family - trust is important.  I love to play with their smaller dog Rocky; I am careful and don’t get mad when Rocky tries to steal my food or bone.  I am improving on my dog walking skills.  As for potty training, I follow whatever Rocky does - Rocky goes outside, so will I. Overall, with love and patience, I will be a great dog for families.  (Even ones with kids, a dog, and a cat!)

After I trust you, I love to cuddle and get attention. I am very sweet and I am looking for someone to love me!

Hi friends! My name is Chief and im a 2.5 year old Pit Mix. I still act like a puppy so it would be great if I had a family that too the time to teach me tricks and manners. Some of the volunteers have spent only a fraction of the time with me that a family gets to and they’ve taught me how to sit and lay down. I’m a really good boy when you have my attention, but sometimes I get distracted by every thing going on around me and forget to focus, but I’m working on it. Anyways, I would love to have an active family. Imagine being an active person and then you’re locked in your room all day except for short breaks every 3 hours. It can be frustrating. But, I’m a happy boy! I need to be the only dog in the home. I just want all of your attention. When it comes to kids I’d prefer that they are 12+ because I am working on those manners. Every one here thinks I’m just so cute. They love my ears ans they think I have the sweetest face. Give me a chance to join your family. Teach me what no one has taken the time to teach me before and I promise I won’t disappoint you!

Love, Chief

animal.description:
A small town city officer was able to convince a neglectful owner to release his suffering dogs. They were taken to the local pound, but their physical conditions and medical needs would have overwhelmed the pound's resources. Napoleon, Cesar, and Shazam had only 24 hours for someone to intervene or they would die. Emaciated, loaded with worms, and with a host of other problems, these puppies were extremely timid and afraid of humans when they arrived at HUA. Months of rehabilitation work by dedicated volunteers and caregivers have paid off. Cesar had big shoes to fill when he moved in with hurricane survivor Nola, whose previous roommate worshipped the ground she walked on. Nola doesn't tolerate fools, but she absolutely tolerates - and even likes - her new buddy Cesar. That is really saying something for this little boy who was so terrified at first. Cesar has bloomed into a happy go lucky fellow who has nothing but wonderful things in store for him.

Visit Cesar at www.hua.org!

"Hello! My name is Theodora and I am a 1-2 year old Treeing Walker Coonhound that came to SVASC when my family was unable to continue to care for me. I am such a sweet pup and am excited to find a new furever home that will be able to love me for who I am. 

When I arrived at SVASC, I was terrified of absolutely everything and am still getting used to my new home, but I am certainly coming around. I did arrive with a pretty nasty, but healed break to my front leg that is still causing me some issues, so SVASC is working on getting that checked out and deciding the best course of action for me. I am in a lot of pain right now, which may be affecting my behavior, but if you give me some time to get to know you, I really do come around and am a total doll baby once I do. 

I have always been an only pet and I do love to be the center of attention. I am open to meeting other dogs to see if we could be a good match though! I also previously lived with kids, but since I am quite nervous, I think that I would do best in an adult only home or a home without young children. I am already house-trained and walk pretty okay on leash. 

My adoption fee is $125 to an approved adopter. If you would like more information on me, please give SVASC a call at (540) 943-5142 or stop by the shelter during open hours. SVASC is located at 1001 Mt. Torrey Rd. Lyndhurst, VA."

animal.description:
Age: Approx. 6 - 7 years (as of 12/09/20)
Weight: 71 lbs (as of 01/28/21)

Location: RI

This dog has been spayed/neutered, is up to date on shots, on heartworm preventative and is microchipped.

Shadow Bear is a laid-back, happy boy!

And handsome and affectionate and smart! We are thinking handsome Shadow Bear is a Black Lab and Chow Chow mix about 6-7 years old. He has the softest, most velvety thick coat, and loves to get pets from his people.
Once he gets to know you, he is affectionate and likes to be in your company. He also likes being brushed which is good as he is bit of a shedder.

He is house trained and is calm in his crate where he sleeps quietly at night. He walks well on the leash in an Easy Walk harness and he is quiet and calm for the most part unless he sees a stranger or hears a strange noise.
True to his Chow Chow roots (a guess only), Shadow Bear will alert bark at strange noises, and when he sees strangers from afar (either from his house window, yard, or on walks). There is no lunging or jumping associated with this response - it is just a vocal alert - and if the stranger or Shadow moves along, he stops his barking. His adopter needs to be comfortable with this, and we will provide a mini-training on how to appropriately handle this behavior.

Shadow is enjoying his time in foster care with another friendly dog and a single woman. He seems to accept men and women equally well, though we haven't observed him living with men. He enjoys the company of his foster sister, who is a sweet, playful dog. He has not taken her up on her polite offers to play, but he also has not be rude or reactive to her and her attempts. We think
h
e would do equally well as a spoiled only dog, or with another dog(s) who can accept that he is more of a co-exister than a player.
Shadow is looking for a cat- and small animal-free home.

Shadow would do best in a low traffic home without many new people coming and going, and in a more quiet than more busy neighborhood. Visitors will need to be managed for their first few visits, but after a few correct introductions/visits, Shadow seems to easily accepts the same visitors. We have not seen Shadow living with children, but for the above reason, we think he would be best suited to an adult-only household. When Shadow has seen children from a distance, he has not seemed phased or too interested.

Shadow Bear is a bit of a couch potato, though he does enjoy his twice daily mile walks. He has been doing great with his New Year's Resolution diet and already lost a few pounds, but he still has about 10lbs to lose. He might become more peppy after shedding those extra pounds and would likely enjoy mild hiking adventures. His nose is ALWAYS working, and would likely love some long-leash time in woods, just smelling all the smells. He also loves care rides, and probably knows the word "RIDE" better than his own name!

Shadow Bear is a sweet and smart boy looking for a chill home, and will make a fabulous companion. Can you make his dream come true? Fill out an application today and let him know that you'd love to have him join your family!

Shadow Bear's Backstory: Shadow was a stray, likely abandoned, and was taken into animal control in spring 2019 in hopes of finding a forever home. He recently was placed with a loving foster family and has settled in so nicely to home life!

Adoption Fee: $585

To apply for this dog, fill out an adoption application on our website: www.sosarl.org/aa/

**Additional info you should know - For most of our dogs, we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each of our dogs as an individual and do our best to describe and place them based on personality not breed label. Some dogs may not yet be in New England, nor ready for immediate adoption. There may be additional vetting, quarantine, waiting periods and/or fees depending upon your state of residence. If you have questions or concerns on any of this, you can discuss this with your Adoption Counselor.

animal.description: Longtime followers of Home Fur Good may remember Lyla, previously known as Coco.  She was a resident at HFG back in the summer of 2018.  Initially, Lyla had an owner who had passed away and she was left living in a closet where people would intermittently toss her some food.  Lyla was adopted by a woman who deeply cared for this shy and loving girl who had a rough start.  An excellent way to help a shy dog is with training.  Training gives them confidence and builds an amazing bond between dog and owner.  When I say that Lyla went to training, I mean she excelled at training.  Just to name a few, she knows sit, stay, come, down, off, paw, kennel up, drop it, and heel.  Lyla’s mom even had her DNA tested to see what made up her 47 pounds.  Lyla’s top three are 25% German Shepherd, 24 % American Pit Bull Terrier, and 15% Boxer.  Lyla’s mom’s living situation changed, and their new home came with a dog.  There was plenty of effort, time, money, and training that went into making a home where they could all coexist, but Lyla was living her life in a muzzle and a crate.  This is not the life meant for such a gentle and intelligent girl.  It was with great sadness and many tears that Lyla has come back to HFG.  It is ok; Lyla will receive her happily ever after.  She turned four years old in July; she is young and has many years left to find a home where she can be the only dog and can be the pampered princess.  Lyla will form a deep bond with an owner that takes the time to practice her training and show Lyla consistency and patience.  She can be wary of strangers; she is very alert and feeds off surrounding energy.  When Lyla sees that everyone is getting along and the mojo is safe and calm, then she becomes the ultimate lapdog, spreading kisses. The adoption fee is $225 and includes spaying/neutering, age-appropriate vaccinations, microchipping, and a free wellness visit at Phoenix Mountain Animal Hospital. Our adoption hours are Thursday-Saturday from 11:00 am-4:00 pm by appointment only.

animal.description:
Hi Friends! I'm Hercules!

***SPECIAL NEEDS***

Intake date: 1/2/2021
Intake type- Surrender- Transfer from Rochester Animal Services
Pup Partners Color: Orange

DOB: 12/15/2010
Weight: 85lbs
Gender: Male

I am: Up to date on vaccines, Neutered and Microchipped

My friends describe me as: Loyal, Affectionate, Goofy, Eager-to- please, Smart

My energy level: Low- I'm a laid back boy who enjoys snuggling. Netflix and a movie sounds nice!

Home with other dogs: It would be best for me to be the only doggo in the home. Plus I would really enjoy all the love and attention

Home with children: Over the age of 12
Home with kitties: No

Hercules found himself at a nearby Animal Control facility after his owner moved and couldn't take him along. Despite him being with that owner since he was 8 weeks old, he's taken the recent changes in his life like a champ! This senior guy may look intimidating, but he's as sweet as a glass of summertime tea. We're looking for a cushy home for him to spend the rest of his life surrounded by comfort, love, and stability. Along with providing a lifetime of love to you, he does come with some special needs:
Hercules was diagnosed with a condition known as KCS, or "dry eye". This condition will require eye medications to be administered to him for the rest of his life because he is no longer able to produce normal tears and his eyes will need to be cleaned out multiple times a day. If his eyes are not kept lubricated/medicated, it leads to painful ulcers.  Luckily, he is a very good boy for his twice a day treatments! Sadly, we suspect he had this condition for some time before entering the shelter, as his eyes look a bit scarred from past ulcers due to non-treatment, and he likely has some vision impairment. His other condition is ataxia in the hind end from an unknown cause. This means his hind end is a bit wobbly/weak due to nerve damage or pressure on his nerves, possibly from a bone spur or some sort of trauma. He doesn't seem to mind at all, but may have trouble with stairs, and of course can't go for major adventures, as that may exacerbate the issue. 

Hercules is a one of a kind boy with the most sweetest soul and disposition. He just wants to be loved and cuddled with at all times. He is a very smart boy and as well as responding to English commands, he responds greatly to Spanish. 

If you may have the right home for this deserving big hunk of a dude, please let us know! If you have further questions or would like to chat about his needs, give us a call @ 607-324-1270 ext 0

animal.description:
Prince was found out in the country in rising flood waters. We were very relieved to have found him before he could come to any harm. As a Dogo Argentino, he is a loveable gentle giant. He loves to play, cherishes his treats and going for long walks. Prince is DEAF. He has been working on his hand signals, a vibration collar and a Herm Sprenger prong collar. He is leash trained and is grasping the hand signals with enthusiasm. Prince needs a strong caregiver that is not intimidated by his size but can give gentle direction and further work with him on his hand signals. Prince is still in the puppy stage and due to his size he would need to meet any potential fur siblings prior to going to his new home. He is currently working on making eye contact with his caregiver for instructions. He knows “Sit”, “No bark” and “No” with hand signals currently. Prince's needs a person who has experience training larger dogs, and can train in a firm, confident, consistent and loving manner. He is a wonderful, fascinating, loyal, affectionate boy.

Visit Prince at www.hua.org!

animal.description:
Meet PONCHO!
-Male
-Approximately 5 years old
-Hound MIX

Poncho is:
-Playful
-Skittish
-Loving
-Nurturing
-Nervous/Anxious
-Shy
-Sweet/Kind
-Crate trained
-Potty trained
-Leash trained
-House trained
-Good with OLDER children (10+)
-Good with other dogs 
-BEHAVIOR AROUND CATS IS UNKNOWN!!!

Poncho is a very LOYAL, SENSITIVE dog who aims to make his humans happy. He thrives off of "good boy" and treats! He LOVES to spend time with his people. It takes him some time to get comfortable around anyone, but once he has adjusted, he becomes the most affectionate dog ever! He is looking for someone that will look at him as the only dog in world, as you to him are his whole world. He makes it known that you are his and his only! If another dog around, he will cry a bit to show his jealousy. 

He LOVES to play! However, he would prefer playing somewhere where he can't hear heavy traffic. He becomes nervous and distracted because of the loud noises.
He will need to continue training on his food aggression. If another dog in the home, it is best to feed him separately. He will need someone who is willing to help him deter from this behavior. 
He is also a bit fearful of men. He is receptive when men speak to him in a loving way, but still is quite nervous. Because of this we suggest a woman becoming his furever. He is the PAWFECT companion and ready to fill your heart with lots of love. 

PONCHO will shine best with:
-Someone looking for a companion
-Women
-Retired but still active
-Somewhere where there is room to play
-Someone willing to train 

If you believe PONCHO could be your forever buddy please fill out an adoption application: https://form.jotform.com/93263081961156

IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS PLEASE EMAIL INFO@MERCYFULLPROJECTS.ORG

BUCKLEY is a seriously handsome senior shih! Ugh! Such a love bug! He is mostly blind and deaf, but that doesn't stop him one bit. He gets along great with other dogs, and even LOVES gentle kids! He does fantastic on a leash and is just a great dog all around.

He came to us from a shelter with AWFUL matted fur and nasty skin, but thanks to lots of TLC and quality vet care, he's on the mend.

Have you ever had a blind or deaf dog? They will love you with their WHOLE hearts! Let's find Buckley a home! To have your home considered for adoption, read about our adoption process or fees, and find out about interstate transport, please visit our website, www.LongWayHomeAdoptables.org and click the adopt tab!

Our adoption fee is $200 for dogs, $100 for cats, and it includes spay/neuter, all vaccines, heartworm testing, fecal testing, deworming, flea/heartworm prevention, and a microchip. 

NATIONWIDE TRANSPORT available for an additional $200 fee. See our website for more info!

Please note: breed listings are based on educated guesses. Shelter animals and abused pets do not come with DNA profiles, so breeds listed on the profile are based on size, coat, markings, and body shape, but are in no way guaranteed. 

_______

Long Way Home is a volunteer organization, comprised of a network of foster homes. Please keep this in mind, as we only have so much time to volunteer around full time jobs, family obligations, etc. It may take us several days to respond.

animal.description:
Meet Bentley!

Bentley enjoys being a positive pup who always finds the good in everything. He has been through some medical trauma. His inquires required him to have intensive physical therapy. Despite all the chaos in his life Bentley acts like nothing has phased him. His tail is always wagging and he cannot wait to jump in your lap for some hugs.

He is working on a full recovery. He would still need to partake in some psychical therapy which would include; swimming, leashed steps and multiple leashed slow walks per day.

Bentley's ideal home is with someone who has the time to commit in helping him gain a full recovery. All he wants to do is jump in your arms and show you affection. He would benefit being an only fur child since he needs a lot of attention. However, he would love to have some human kids in the household. He has such a go with the flow attitude that he should have no problem regaining his strength.

He, Ashley, Cleopatra, Liz Taylor, Lucille Ball and Mary Kate were all surrendered to ATDR because of the death of their precious person. Frightened, not understanding what's going on in their world, they are now in a safe, loving foster home being cared for and receiving any needed veterinary care. This good-looking group was obviously well loved but a bit overfed! While bringing their health needs up to speed, their foster mom is working on gaining their trust, making them feel at home and has put them on a nutritious diet to hopefully slim them down some. Stay tuned as we learn more about these beautiful orphaned babies to share here.Each of these pups will need to go to a home with a companion dog to share life with. In the meantime, if you have it in your heart to adopt one or more of these precious pups and give them the love and security they need again, please submit an adoption application for any or all of them! animal.description:
Howie has been in a long-term foster home, but due to a change of circumstances, we are looking for a new adoptive or foster home for him.  Howie has EPI - Exocrine pancreatic insufficiency.

Exocrine pancreatic insufficiency occurs when the pancreas does not release enough digestive enzymes.  As a result, food is not digested properly, and the body doesn’t receive the nutrition it needs. 

Howie's EPI is under control and not difficult at all to manage.

From his current foster mom:

Howie is really an awesome dog. He is very intelligent and happy. He is content to sit on the sofa most days but does enjoy playtime in the yard. Howie is also a huge fan of his toys! He will usually pick one and play with that toy most of the day. While he enjoys playing with his current housemates, Howie would do best in a home with no small animals or young children. 

Howie's EPI has become extremely easy to manage. We currently feed him Pure Balance Grain Free Salmon from Walmart, which he loves. The Enzyme powder simply needs to be mixed with the food with tepid water and allowed to soak for 20-30 minutes. He has been doing amazingly well with this easy process.

This handsome boy is about 4 years old. If you think Howie would be a good fit in your home, please fill out an application here:

http://www.savingpawsrescueaz.org/dogs/

If you can give Howie  an indoor forever 
home, please fill out our online application on our website at http://www.savingpawsrescueaz.com/adoption-form/  

 We will only schedule meet and greets with an approved application. We are an all-volunteer organization.  It may take a couple of days to process an application and complete reference checks.

Thank you for your interest in saving the life of a dog.
animal.name: Howie

animal.description:
"Hiya! My name is Karate Kid and I'm a 1-ish your old German Shepherd/Beagle mix. I came to SVASC when my previous owner was no longer able to care for me, so now I'm looking for a brand new family to call my own. What do you think about taking a handsome stud muffin like me home with ya? 

After speaking with my previous owner, SVASC got a pretty good story about my past, before my previous caretaker ever had him. Unfortunately, my past is pretty grim and I'm still working through that, but I'm happy to be out of that situation and excited to move on to bigger and better things! While my personality is back to 100%, my body is still healing and I actually do have a fractured pelvis. Yikes! I know, I know, but lucking SVASC and their pawtners over at Friends of SVASC are getting that taken care of. Soon, I'll be feeling like a million bucks! 

At a year old, I still have loads of energy and I'm not letting that injury slow me down any. I love to play and can be quite a rough player, so I would do best in a home without young kids, as I get very excited and do still play bite and jump sometimes. I can be a little picky about my doggy friends and would do best in a home with only other calmer pups or as an only pooch. This may change as my pelvis heals up, though. Anyways, I'm ready to go home, what about you? 

My adoption fee is $125 to an approved adopter. If you would like more information on me, please give SVASC a call at (540) 943-5142 or stop by the shelter during open hours. SVASC is located at 1001 Mt. Torrey Rd. Lyndhurst, VA."
animal.name: Karate Kid

animal.description:
Adoption Fee: $350.00

***Owning a Bulldog requires special knowledge and care; it can be a substantial financial undertaking as they age. Serious inquiries only! Looking for well informed adopters, preferably with previous experience owning a bulldog or similar breed. ***

Although he appears manly, 4 year old Olde English Bulldog Duke is a spoiled princess at heart. He enjoys being the center of attention, craves affection from his people and does not like to be left alone. Weighing in at 84 pounds, he is strong and playful! He:
•	Is house trained
•	Walks nicely on a slip lead
•	Needs to be the only dog - but with training and continued socialization may accept another in the future
•	Is not appropriate for a home with children
•	Rides well in a vehicle
•	Is medium to high energy
Happy and upbeat, Duke needs a home that has a lot of time to devote to play, training and cuddles. Structure and a firm handler are a must for this gorgeous dog as he does at times demonstrate hard-headedness common to bulldogs. Very much a house dog, he is content spending time indoors if given outlets for exercise. He will make a knowledgeable family a truly loving companion.

Duke is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, and heartworm negative. 

For more information about Duke or our shelter please call us at (830) 693-0569 or visit our website at highlandlakescaninerescue.org 

If you would like to schedule a meet and greet with Duke or any of our dogs, please fill out an application at highlandlakescaninerescue.org/application-for-adoption

animal.description:
Ella Mae is very shy/skittish- she will need a securely fenced yard and a friendly dog buddy in the home and no children under 13 years old.

Hi, I'm Ella Mae. I am very shy but my foster mom says I am very sweet too. I am an 8 month old Pit Bull Terrier mix puppy. I found my way to Puppy Paws after my owner passed away. My foster family has been taking such good care of me. They are teaching me how to be an inside dog and turns out I really love it- especially the cozy dog beds and snuggles. My foster mom says I am very smart! I have learned my potty training and will even scratch the door to tell her I want to go out! I will need a family that is patient and understands that I need time to feel safe and comfortable in my new home- I've been through a lot of changes lately. I will need a fenced in yard to run and play- I love to run zoomies! I would love a quieter neighborhood- I'm not sure if I am ready for the hustle and bustle of city life. I will also need a  home with another friendly dog  - I absolutely adore my doggie foster sister.  I am gaining so much confidence with her help and I love to snuggle with her. My foster mom says I have blossomed so much since I met her. Now I am looking for a forever family with the patience and understanding to help me continue my journey and help me grow in confidence. If you think that could be you, please go to puppypawsrescue.org and apply!


If interested in adopting please fill out our no obligation online application at www.puppypawsrescue.org 

Note: Our rescue requires that all adopter's current and prior animals are up-to-date on vaccinations (DHLPP & Rabies)  and preventatives (heartworm and flea and tick), unless there is a medical reason not allowing it. All animals in your household should be spayed or neutered unless medically indicated that they should not be or are currently still too young.

animal.description:
Lulu Belle is a female, 26 lb., chocolate and white Border Collie mix. Lulu Belle's estimated date of birth is December, 2019. She came to ARF as an owner surrender. She is the perfect combination of playful and cuddly. She likes going on walks, playing fetch, zooming around the yard, and cuddling up next to her human on the couch or in bed.  She is housetrained and knows how to sit on command.  When she’s excited, she gives the silliest, toothiest smile a dog can give. 

Lulu Belle was owner surrendered by a woman who said that she barked too much in her apartment.  Lulu Belle is very sensitive to noises and meeting new people (especially men) or being in new situations is scary at first.  Her former owner said that she lived with three children and did well with them; she seems to want to be friends with children that she meets on walks but is also anxious about them, so she may have been mistreated by them in the past.  She has the Border Collie intelligence and learns new things quickly.  She needs a calm, stable home that can help her learn that people are good and can be trusted.  Does that home sound like yours?  Lulu Belle would love nothing more than to have a home and people to call her own. Lulu Belle has a $150.00 adoption fee plus the cost of 6 months of heartworm prevention.  

Note: ARF reserves the right to deny any application that is deemed unsuitable for the animal. Please be aware that our animal adoptions are NOT on a first come- first serve basis. Our sole purpose is to find the best possible home for the animals that fall under our care. We do not ship our animals. All adopters are expected to come to Tulsa if approved.

For details on how to adopt please visit http://www.arftulsa.org/adopt.

If you are not local to us we encourage you to look at rescues and shelters in your area as many animals are in need across the United States.
If you have previously applied with us please email adoptionatmars@gmail.com to reactivate your application with new interest.

or

PETFINDER VIEWERS: Find our applications at www.midwestanimalrescue.org

*The pet you are viewing is a rescued pet which is most often from an animal control facility and does not come with a pedigree. The breed(s) listed are our best guess and are in no way guaranteed. Sometimes the pets appear to be a particular breed(s) in the pictures we receive from our rescue partners and when they arrive we are surprised to see an entirely different breed(s) in person! If you choose to DNA test your adopted pet, test results may vary from company to company and our breed guess may not be reflected in those results as it is just that, our best guess. It is with deep longing that we wish there was a breed called "cute" as we believe all of our dogs would fall under this new breed classification!

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Gorgeous young Bulldog in need of TENDER LOVING CARE. Read to the end. Applications being taken. Click on 'adopt' and complete application.
Ember was surrendered due to health issues of her owner. Her breed was stated as English Bulldog but she does not have papers and appears to have traits of the American Bulldog. Regardless of the specific breed, Ember will need an owner that is familiar with the health issues of Bulldogs. Ember is a lover, very affectionate. She has 2 speeds, full on and resting. She tires easily after high energy play, watch her video below. Ember loves to have whole body massages, she tolerates baths, she thinks she is small and wants to get into your lap. Walks well on leash but can pull if she sees another animal. Will need heavy duty toys and beds.At only 7 months, she is solid-heavy. As for children, she loves them but she was not corrected about jumping up on people. Her owner was knocked down on several occations by Ember's excited activity and was a primary part of the reason for her surrender. We believe that Ember will do best in a home as an ONLY PET. She does play hard with other similar sized dogs, but with brachycephalic syndrome (smushed nose) her breathing is impaired and can over heat quickly. She snores loudly and can be heard over 30 feet away. Previously, Ember was left all day in a crate (over 10 hours) and she now has some separation anxiety. So her forever home will need to have only short periods of her being crated or left alone. She does BARK and CRY when she is left, so not a good fit for apartment living unless owner is mostly stay at home or takes her when they leave. She will dig if left alone in yard. (Doggy door may help with this)Micro-chippedAdoption Fee $400

animal.description:
Wilson – Staffordshire Terrier mix – 8yrs. – male (56 lbs.)

Introducing our distinguished gentleman, Wilson. He lived in the same home his entire life, then was dumped at a county shelter when his owner got pregnant. They said since they had not ever had him around babies, they didn’t want to take a chance. Unbelievable! Poor Wilson never even got the chance to show them that he could be good with babies... and he was their first baby! It’s absolutely heartbreaking. At the county shelter he completely shut down and just sat on his bed and shook – we needed to get him out of there. Now, he’s with us and doing MUCH better! We treat Wilson with the respect he should get being that he’s a senior boy – he gets to be our lobby dog, aka kennel assistant. Which means he has his own room in the lobby area and gets to be out and about when our staff are there. Wilson likes everyone and wags his tail with such enthusiasm that it becomes a weapon. And though he may have some gray on his face, you would never guess his age by his actions – he’s active, friendly, and loves to go for long walks. He is completely housebroken and very good inside. Because he was never around kids, we believe that his best home would be either no children or teens and up. This boy is sweet, affectionate, and funny – he’s just happy to be close. If our sweet boy seems like a good match for your life, please fill out an application to get the honor of meeting him.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

This is Mabel. She's a good girl. Mabel is a retiree boxer/pit mix with a big heart, sweet/loyal disposition that is looking for her forever retirement home. Mabel's estimated DOB is 6/1/2010.

Mabel will need a forever home that has humans at home nearly every day. Either a family with someone retired or working from home would be a great fit for her. This is only because of her anxiety with being crated or kenneled.

When she arrived to Minnesota
she was heart-worm positive. It's a very rough treatment, but thanks to Wags & Whiskers, she successfully finished it and has been deemed safe to be a normal dog again! With that said, she is like any other dog and will need monthly heart worm preventatives, and now she knows how important that is for every dog to begin with!

Mabel had a long, hard road before being rescued by Wags & Whiskers. It's safe to assume she's been a mom to many puppies over her years. Her body is showing the typical signs of a hard-working mom who needs a vacation! Upon arrival she had multiple mammary masses that needed removed. It was also apparent that she had not received any good dental care like she should. Being heartworm positive, this made it quite the fiasco to treat! But soon after her heartworms were taken care of, we gave Mabel all of the medical attention she so badly needed. She now has a clean bill of health for her teeth and masses. She had 5 teeth removed completely and does just fine. The areas from her mass removals look great and healed well! Of course she still is a senior lady, so she can be hard of hearing and is somewhat blind in both eyes. She also has some urinary incontinence. Being a retired puppy mom is hard! She takes a daily pill for this, and as her foster mom I can tell you this is no big deal and easily taken care of. She does very well despite all of this and has the best personality to boot, but it should be noted so her forever home knows how special she is!

Now on to non-medical things....like her shining star personality! If you ever wanted a dog that will look you in the eyes and melt your heart because you KNOW that she is saying thank you...Mabel is your girl.

She has two favorite things: naps and being with you, her human. Somehow, through all that Mabel has endured, she truly has never lost her love for all things human. This is especially impressive, as she does have apparent signs of mistreatment in her previous life. She flinches at touch (just initially until she immediately starts wagging her tail) and is terrified of cages. Despite all this, a smiling face and a wagging tail is given to everyone she meets, no exceptions.

She does great with children (which can be hard to find for senior dogs sometimes!) and wants to be in whatever room you're in. Her main goal in life is a warm, comfortable place to sleep that is close enough to you so she can stare into your soul. She does typically sleep most of the day, with random spurts of energy based on your schedule and desire. You want to go for a walk? She's game! You want to watch netflix and have a lazy day? She's game!

She will tell you when she needs to use the bathroom, by staring at you with a whimper. You likely won't ever hear her bark unless another dog is in her sights. She rarely has house accidents, even with her incontinence from age, if she is kept on a regular schedule. That being said, she is like any other dog...she can only keep it in so long if you forget! She currently lives in an unfenced yard and does just fine on a tie-out when going potty.

Mabel does have one piece of trauma she brought with her from her life before rescue. She does not get along with other dogs. We aren't sure what happened to her before rescue, but it caused quite the fear and mistrust of other dogs. She is what we call "dog reactive" to an extreme measure, so she should not be around other dogs nor ever introduced to an area with other dogs free roaming such as a dog park. If she does have interaction with another dog, she becomes aggressive towards said dog and with her limited hearing and sight, it can be difficult to redirect her. She should be on leash or in a fenced in yard at all times for this reason and cannot live with any other dogs, no exceptions.

Cats, however, she does fine with. She currently lives with two sassy cats and coexists with them great. They call the shots and Mabel just plays by their rules. Her only caviat is making sure there is no food/treat in the reach of both Mabel and the cats, otherwise she will nip or bark at them in defense of her precious morsels!

Mabel has separation anxiety. Along with whatever made her scared of dogs in her past life, also made her very scared of losing you. You will have yourself a Mabel shaped shadow if you go too far. She wants to be by your side! We give Mabel some medication to relax her if we know she will be left at home alone. She will bark (the only time you'll ever hear her bark) when she is kenneled, no shared walls of apartments for this gal. She can only be left at home in what we call "the Alcatraz kennel." A kennel that is heavy duty and unable for her to sneak out of. These kennels are a must have for any dog with separation anxiety and she will destroy a regular kennel if tried.

She loves car rides! If you need a road trip companion, she is down to clown. She loves being in the car for errands, long trips, anything. We find it hilarious that she willingly jumps into any vehicle, despite what her mother probably told her about taking rides from strangers! Silly Mabel.

She loves a good walk and a good sniff if you can remember not to let her have any other dog within her reach. She will gladly say hello to every kid and human on the other hand. She is still working on her walking manners. She's always a bit excited to be out on the town so we are still working on the not pulling part! This "going for a walk" thing is so cool to her, she is trying hard to be a good girl during all of it!

She knows how to shake paw, sit, go lay down, come, and more. An old dog can learn new tricks! She would love the chance to prove it to you! She does not chew on or play with toys at all. This is probably because of her lack of past dental care. She does, however, enjoy a good kong of peanut butter and gumming/chewing a good bully stick. She currently eats only wet food, or dry dog food that has been softened a bit with some water. We are pretty sure that dry food is just too painful for her to eat, as she will completely ignore it.

At night, Mabel sleeps with us at the foot of our bed. Her fear of crates and separation do make it difficult for her to sleep outside of your room. She prefers to at least be on a comfy bed on the floor, as long as it's in the room you sleep in too.

Mabel still has lots of love to give. We know she has quite the story, but she is hoping someone is willing to hear this story and check her out. She would make a great addition to a home that is busy or not busy, as long as there is a human at home generally most of time. No other dogs around or access to dogs is also important to her, along with the understanding that she is a senior and may just need your couch spot for a good nap. Mabel will need a kind and patient home that is willing to learn the joys and caviats of senior doggy care.

If you have a home that sounds like a good fit and a heart that is open and ready for some loving, I promise Mabel will tell you every day, that you are her favorite human that ever did walk this earth.

Interested in adopting this lovable animal? Please go to our website www.wagsmn.org and fill out an Adoption Application. Once the application is processed, a Wags representative will contact you, answer any questions you may have, and set up a time/location for a meet and greet! A home visit is required prior to adoption.

Thank you for choosing to adopt!

Breed and temperament determination: Wags & Whiskers Animal Rescue attempts to determine breed and temperament using a combination of looks, information provided to us at intake, and our experience with the animal while in our Rescue. We do not guarantee this determination.

This handsome boy is Cooper! Cooper is a very sweet but young and untrained. He is a 1 year old Neutered male Siberian Husky. Cooper would do best in a home that has experience with Huskies and their ways. He can be very mouthy and needs someone who can give him consistency and training. Cooper is a beautiful all white pup with medium length hair. He has gorgeous ice blue eyes that look into your soul! 
Cooper came to BARK after being found as a stray dog. He has since been neutered and all of his vaccinations have been updated. He has also been microchipped. Cooper tends to give tiny nips while playing and over stimulated so a home without children is requested. He is alright with other dogs, but a slow introduction is a MUST. He can be very nervous at first meeting and will tend to shake when nervous. 
Coopers ideal home would be with an adult who has time and patience to train this sweet boy to become the perfect dog he is meant to be.

animal.description:
Snapshot of Churro!

Size?
Im a puppy but still growing!

Age? 3 months
Activity Level?
I play hard and sleep hard!

Noise Level?
I like to alert people when something is happening!

Good with Dogs?
Untested but likely fine!

Good with Cats?
Untested but likely fine!

Good with Kids?
Untested but likely fine!

Good with Strangers?
I like to take it slow with some distance!

Potty Trained?
I'm a puppy and still working on it!

Crate Trained?
I bark for a little, but quiet down quickly!

Interested? Learn more about Churro below!

About Churro:

My name is Churro! I came from South Dakota in early December. The clinic told my foster mom that I am 3 months old and am a lab mix. I do enjoy playing hard, my litter mate and I love to wrestle!

I have not had any exposure to dogs outside my litter since I arrived here in the Cities. I think I would do alright if I was introduced slowly. I have not met any cats or small children but would expect that we would get along just fine as long as they respect my boundaries!

I like my crate but I am still learning to sleep through the night. I am doing well on the leash, but most of our outings have been short trips around the block. I was just neutered, so my family wants to make sure that I am fully recovered before we venture too far from home. I am a quick-learner and am very treat-motivated. I have learned my basic commands (sit, come, and crate) and I am working on stay. House-training is going well! As long as we stick to the schedule, I expect to have this mastered in no time. At the end of the day, I do like to sit on the couch with my people and chew on a bone or one of my toys to wind down.

Adoption Fee: $550

Training Requirement: Obedience Training 1

*Foster to Adopt: I am looking for a forever home now, but I still need all my puppy shots! So I'm looking for a family that will be able to commit to bringing me to all of my appointments with TCPR until I'm ready to be fully adopted by you!

MEET ME/ADOPT ME: If you'd like to arrange a meeting or begin the adoption process, please fill out an adoption application by visiting www.twincitiespetrescue.org/adopt/adopt-a-dog/ . A volunteer from Twin Cities Pet Rescue will contact you once your application is reviewed.

FOSTER HOMES NEEDED!!! Twin Cities Pet Rescue is a volunteer-run, foster home-based organization. We can only rescue as many animals as available foster homes. Please consider saving the life of an animal in need and become a volunteer foster home today. To become a foster, fill out a dog or cat foster application on the Twin Cities Pet Rescue website: www.twincitiespetrescue.org . There is little to no cost to foster an animal. Twin Cities Pet Rescue provides its foster families with food, supplies, and veterinary care for its animals. All you need to do is supply the love!

PLEASE NOTE: Twin Cities Pet Rescue does not adopt to homes further than 60 miles from the Minneapolis/St. Paul Metro Area.
