animal.description:
Happy, happy, joy, joy—this is the best way to describe Miss Alaska’s personality. This young Great Pyrenees girl didn’t have a great start in life but she isn’t looking back—the sky is the limit! Alaska has a way about her that one can’t help but love...especially after seeing her face with that inviting smile and contagious, positive attitude. She is very respectful of everything asked of her—grooming, keeping her kennel clean, riding in the car, going in her kennel when asked. She had never been on a leash, so will need a person(s) willing to take her for consistent walks to continue her training. If we had to give Alaska a theme song it would be “girls just want to have fun” :) She loves, loves, loves to play and will do everything in her power to entice even the grumpiest dogs to play while somehow managing to respect their space. No worries, because she loves to play with people equally. She greets her human every morning by running up, bowing down and giving her a look inviting play. Cats are a no for this girl but older children are a yes! Alaska needs a home with a family who will appreciate her zest for life, the time and desire to play and continue her training, a large fenced yard, a playful dog would be a bonus but not required for the right family—are you the active, fun family Alaska is waiting for?

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

Jessa is about 2 years old and a perfect 50 pounds full grown! Shes super smart at learning her commands, loves belly rubs and is even crate and potty trained WHAT A GEM. Jessa does take some time to adjust in a new environment, and her ideal home would be with a household experienced with large breeds. Jessa cant wait to find a home to give her all the love and affection shes been missing out on. Is Jessa the one you need in your life?

animal.description: Meet Choppa who is a very special boy! Choppa came to us with severe allergies. His paws were swollen to twice their normal size and he was red with irritation over his entire body, to the point, he had lost fur in some of the locations. Allergies can be difficult to diagnose on any dog, but with Choppa being as young as he is, we wanted to make sure he had a chance! We switched his food over to a different protein and we ordered him a dose of Cytopoint. Choppa no longer looks like the same dog! The Cytopoint runs around $154.97 for a dose and a dose lasts 8-12 weeks. Choppa had the injection on 12/2 and he still looks great! So his adopter will need to be able to provide for his allergies as needed. Choppa formerly lived with a Poodle and his previous owner says he loves people and other dogs but has never been around cats. (NOTE: We do require dog-to-dog meet and greets if you already own a canine and are interested in adopting Choppa!) His previous owner also related that he is housetrained, but new adopters should always expect an accident or two as Choppa falls into his new schedule! He loves squeaky toys and will play with them by himself. He also knows Sit and Paw. As a young, strong dog who is still learning his manners, older children are recommended. He is strong on leash, but luckily, the HSWC has just partnered with GoodPup! and Choppa can receive a free week of training and the adopter will get 20% off training for life (your life!). Choppa is enjoying quiet time in the back of the shelter, so you will not see him on our Adoption floor but please ask to meet him! We think you will fall in love!

Charlie is approximately seven year old ten pound Shipoo.  That is a Shitzu Poodle mix.  He is house trained, neutered, microchipped, current on all vaccinations, heart worm negative and on a preventative.
Charlie only has two teeth but it does not stop him from enjoying his kibble.  He is very treat motivated.  Charlie is a true cuddle bug.

** The Texas Comptroller now requires sales tax on adoption fees.

** Temporarily Suspended due to COVID ** Monthly Meet & Greets  (12:00 - 2:00)
Petco (in Leander) every 1st Saturday of the month
Pet Supplies Plus (Parmer & Mopac) every third Saturday of the month


** Please note: Due to their size, our dogs are not suitable for homes with children under 5..

We do not have a facility, all dogs are fostered in the homes of our volunteers. If you are interested in adopting a dog from Lil' Paws Maltese Rescue and other Petite Paws, please visit our website at www.lilpaws-malteserescue.org and fill out an adoption application. This is the first step in our adoption process. Our goal is to place our dogs in safe, stable and loving homes in the Austin Metropolitan area. Thanks for looking!

Lil' Paws Maltese Rescue and other Petite Paws depends on donations to keep the dogs in our program healthy. Many health issues are taken care of before a dog leaves a rescue: spaying, neutering, immunizations, dental care, and in some cases major surgery. Because of the cost of this care, donations are essential to enable us to continue our work. If you would like to show appreciation for what we do and help us continue to do it please go to our website homepage and click the donate button. We thank you in advance for your support.

animal.description:
Noelle is a 2-3 year old, 56 lb, Coonhound/Retriever mix (best guess!). She was found as a stray in South Carolina so not much is known about her past, but she has been in a foster home in NH since 1/17, where her fosters are learning all about her personality.  
  
Not only is she stunning with a rich black and mahogany coat, Noelle is SO happy and a total sweetheart. ALL the time! Haven't seen a mean bone in her body. She absolutely loves people and bonds quickly. She would love to be in a home where she could be included in many activities with her humans! Noelle walks well with her Freedom harness on and with her medium-high energy, she would make a great walking, running, or hiking companion. Off-leash adventures might not be the best option for her without further training, due to the risks of her following her hound nose after smells and critters. She would love a fenced in yard where she is happy to run and she will entertain herself with some fun toys. 
  
Noelle is friendly and playful with other dogs, but she does play very hard and fast and may be a bit overly rambunctious for some dogs, and may accidentally scratch or knock over small children. Noelle did do well with a 3 year old child and cats in the home when she was first picked up as a stray. She does not always pick up on other dog's cues/warnings to be left alone, she is learning. Noelle is comfortable being handled for baths, looking in ears, lifting up paws, wearing sweaters, wearing harnesses, etc. - in fact, she prefers that you be touching her at all times. She loves attention!  
 
Noelle does have some puppy-like tendencies and needs continued training and guidance. But she is crate trained, potty trained, receptive to coming when called, has learned sit, is getting better about jumping by the day. With consistency she will pick up things quickly and is very eager to please! She accompanies her foster mom to work in a boarding facility and is very calm and quiet in her kennel suite. She's also very quiet when in her crate in the house. She whines sometimes, but very rarely barks at anything.  
  
Noelle tested positive for heartworm when she arrived at the shelter in December 2020 and is currently going through treatment plan. 
  
Apply to adopt here: http://longtraildogs.org/adoption-application/ e-mail lisa@longtraildogs.org for more info.

animal.description:
Collette originally came in the shelter in February of 2020. The family who owned her, only had her a short 2 days before they came to the decision that she was just not the right fit for their family. They were looking for more of a hunter, and Collette is just too skittish of a personality for that. 
As stated above Collette is a skittish dog, and she really lacks in her confidence when dealing with new people and situations. When she was a young puppy she may not have been socialized and coming to a shelter setting as she was maturing was not ideal, since she basically grew up here, during a pandemic, and that limited her exposure to new people, events, and better socialization.
Collette is one of the shelters special personalities, and it is going to take time, patience, and understanding from her new home to help her to develop the bond that she needs to build that confidence. She would benefit most from living with a single person as she does develop strong bonds to some people, but she may do ok with some couples. But that couple will have to make sure they both share in her care equally, or she will develop a stronger bond with one and she may feel the need to guard them. 
If Collette can find someone with experience, and patience, in return they will be rewarded with a wonderful companion.

Athena was found as a stray running the streets, hugely pregnant. She was so grateful to be saved, and gave birth to a whole bunch of fat, bouncing babies days after coming to HUA. She was an attentive and protective mother, even making sure that the runt of the litter got every chance she needed to survive and thrive. Now that Athena's babies have all found their new homes, Athena is ready to become somebody's baby. Besides being the prettiest thing, she is the sweetest thing. She loves treats, walks, toys, tennis balls, car rides and playing outdoors. She has gotten along quite nicely with the other dogs, even those who play a bit rough. She was a master of her obedience and agility classes. Athena has been a brave and tolerant dog -- she deserves a life of pampering and happiness, and she would prefer no small children that may be too rambunctious for her.. Her family will be rewarded with constant grins and epic butt wiggles.

Visit Athena at www.hua.org!

animal.description:
Brighten your world and add a dash of spice to your life - meet Dega! Dega came to THS after his owner had some health issues and could no longer care for him. However, that hasn't dampened his love of the world and people, and he's ready to love his new forever family just as much!

Dega is a very active and loving boy who will keep you on your toes! Fetch is his absolute favorite pasttime, especially if you have tennis balls. If you don't, we recommend that you stock up quickly! Dega's previous family ranted and raved about how intelligent this sweet boy was - he is a super fast learner when it comes to tricks, and walks great on a leash. His person favorite trick is "shake" because it always got him the most treats, but he also knows sit, stay, and come! He is food-motivated and ready to learn and impress his new forever family with his pawesome skills, but at the end of the day, Dega is very affectionate and just loves to be around his people as much as he can.

In Dega's previous home, he lived with many adults and another dog and got along swimmingly with everyone! Dega would like to meet any resident dogs before going home to make sure they are a good match. He is not friendly with cats. Dega has been able to jump/climb shorter fences and should have a secure fence or regular leash-walking in his new home. He loves to spend time with his people so he won't mind being supervised when outside! 

Dega had an incident in a previous home where he had been suddenly uncomfortable with a male visitor. Although he's generally a social butterfly, he would like to meet all members of his household before going home to ensure he will be a good fit. 

Please follow this link to learn more about our current adoption process: https://toledohumane.org/covid-19-update

animal.description: Cricket is "the most". She is undeniably "the most" cuddly, energetic, fun, curious and sweetest girl I have ever fostered. Although she has already had a litter, the vet thinks she is only about 18-20 months old. She is still very much a playful puppy in many ways. She is housebroken, will "sit" on command and knows what "no" means. She is an inside dog and loves to cuddle with you on your favorite chair and if she has her way, sleep with you at night. :-). She would love to be your buddy and companion, doing what you do and going where you go. She also has a little fetish about "chilling out" on various tables tops. :) She is very funny. Her energy level would be great with another energetic and tolerant dog or somebody that wants to take long walks or jog with her daily. She loves to fetch and play tug-of-war. Her sweet and energetic disposition displays "play aggression" but no animosity. Because of her size, strength and playfulness she would probably do best in a home with another energetic, playful and tolerant dog and/or older children.

animal.description:
YOU MUST HAVE AN APPROVED APPLICATION IN ORDER TO MEET OUR PETS.

Leo is a 65 pound blue nose Pit Bull and Boxer mix youngster. Leo just turned one year old on October 28th 2020.

He was adopted by his foster moms former roommate in June from a mutual friend of ours. Last month, she moved into an apartment closer to the city expecting to take Leo with her. Unfortunately she was unable to continue caring for him in her new home and requested I care for him until he could find a new home. Foster mom has grown very fond of Leo but cannot keep him since she works full time and already has a dog of her own, his brother Aries. 

Leo is one of the kindest and most loving dogs foster mom has ever had the pleasure of homing. He is very expressive, very empathetic and gentle, even though he can be quite clumsy. 

That being said, Leo did not get the attention he deserved in his early months. He was adopted and rehomed once or twice before coming to live in his foster home in June of 2020 and because of that, his training was inconsistent. 

Leo knows his name, the commands sit and paw, but does not always feel motivated to respond to these commands and has been slow to pick up others. While he does not yet respond to stay, Leo will sit and wait patiently for his food to be placed on the floor before he eats. 

Leo loves to chew and has been known to snack on furniture, pillows and other household items within his reach however is less likely to do so the more toys and chew bones of his own he has. All he needs is redirection and consistency. Remember, he is still really just a big puppy!

Leo is not food aggressive in the slightest! He is open to sharing snacks and toys and although he can be playfully possessive, it is only ever in hopes that he can start a friendly game of tug of war. 

Leo can sometimes be shy in front of other dogs (especially male dogs) and sometimes relies on his brother Aries to break the ice, however once he is made comfortable, you will never see a truer friendship than that which he offers, so while I remain cautious upon introductions, I do not consider Leo to be dog aggressive. 

Leo is partially house trained. He does not have a specific way of notifying you he needs to be let out and sometimes he will start pacing very quickly but not always. I normally keep track of the time between his last walk and last meal to know when he might have to go next, however I do rely on pee pads for him, which if provided he will use as opposed to going directly on the floor. 

Leo will be neutered and vaccinated before adoption.

Leo needs a permanent home where he will be seen as a priority, and given the individualized attention he very much deserves. 

Adoptiin donation $125.

Please note that we do not ship animals. We also require a home visit before finalizing any adoptions so preference is given to applicants within a 90 mile range. You will be required to come to High Point, NC to meet/pick up your new pet.

HOW TO APPLY:
1. Go to www.lovingpetinnadoptions.org
2. Click on the "Adoption Application" link on the left side of the page.
3. The application will open as a PDF and you should have the ability to fill it in from that page. Be sure to complete all fields.
4. Save the application to your computer, then attach in an email and send to petprojectnc@gmail.com
5. Someone will review your application as soon as possible, usually within 24 hours, and will be in touch with next steps.

animal.description:
Benny is an almost 5-year-old foxhound/beagle mix. He was adopted through P&C around 4 months old after he was hit by a car. Benny still has a "flat tire" front foot, and doesn't like to go long walks (2+ miles) because of this. He is allergic to eggs, and has had skin issues with many dog foods and most treats. We have been purchasing Kirklands premium dog food for him (Very reasonable, from Costco) and giving him baby carrots as treats and have had NO skin allergy issues since. Benny is an indoor dog, he will bark if left outside. He is crate trained, but prefers to sleep on his doggie bed at night. He is completely housebroken and never has accidents. He is able to wait long periods of time before needing to go out. He likes going on walks and can fetch. He is most content to lay in the sun (inside) like a huge cat and nuzzle you. He doesn't bark unless someone comes in the the yard, to the front door, or if he sees other animals. He is not cat friendly, but does fine with most dogs. He knows the following commands: sit, shake, no, and "go to bed", he will go in the house if you say "go to bed" while outside. If inside, he'll actually go to his bed. We are looking for a foster/adopter for Benny. Older children only please. Benny does have some possessive quirks to him that we will need to talk to each possible adopter about. Please fill out an application to foster/adopt at https://www.pupandcatco.com/We do not have a shelter facility and our pets are housed in foster homes, vet clinics and local boarding facilities.

Many of our adoptable pets attend adoption events each Saturday at Mall of Georgia Petsmart in Buford, Georgia from 11:30-3:00 pm

Please check with us to find out if a particular pet will be available. Dogs going to adoption event are typically posted on our Facebook page the day prior.

Details about our adoption procedures can be seen at www.pupandcatco.com.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 8/18/2019
Reason for being in rescue: Rafiki was found as a stray and taken to a local NC shelter. CPR pulled him from the shelter.
Foster location: Foster Home in Raleigh, NC
Special Needs? Rafiki walks with an interesting gait for unknown reasons. This could be from an extended period of neglect. Rafiki is sensitive about his feet and muzzle but is getting better every day. He recently went to the vet for a nail trim and the tech said he did very well. We do believe that he still requires sedation grooming as the sound of clippers near his head and feet makes him nervous and can cause him to lash out. We will explore this more when he grows out from his last groom.
Weight: 59 lbs - Rafiki is working on weight loss in his foster home
Height: 24 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $499

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Rafiki is not a dog for a first-time owner. He is a 6-year-old who has clearly faced challenges. He is used to playing by his rules and can be stubborn but does want to please his people. Rafiki's ideal owner is an experienced and patient standard poodle owner. Rafiki gets along well with other dogs both large and small but does not require a playmate. He would be happy as an only dog or with another mature dog that will respect his boundaries. He is indifferent to cats.

Given his sensitivities Rafiki is not a dog for a home with small children. Our perfect home for Rafiki will be an adult only home. He does well with adults and once you earn his trust and he knows you are a reliable source of attention; he is a love bug. Rafiki is not high energy, preferring to walk around the yard with you, go for a quiet walk or laze around the house.

What is my personality like? Rafiki is named after the character in the Lion King. Like the Disney character, Rafiki has an outward personality that is eccentric and somewhat goofy. His bark is deep and somewhat hoarse. But a look deeper into this boy's eyes will show you a dog with a huge heart, a caring soul, and a strong desire to make deep connections.

Rafiki arrived at Dreamweaver Farms a mess. He was at least 15 pounds underweight, deeply matted, and the chaos of all the new experiences of being at a rescue was daunting. It took 3 days before he could hold down food. And almost 2 weeks before the light returned to his eyes. Through this all, Rafiki watched. He watched his caregivers. He watched the dogs around him. And he learned the routine.

Rafiki was found wandering the streets and had likely been there for a while. Food and grooming were far removed. But it is clear he was once someone's pet. This beautiful boy walks great on a leash, is crate trained, and gets along well with other dogs. In his foster home he is impeccably house trained. Rafiki has not had much experience riding in cars and his behavior in a car needs work. He becomes overly excited reacting to traffic and strangers.

Rafiki's time on the streets has left its mark on him. He will growl to warn you if he does not want to do something. He will snarl and bite if you push him. Rafiki needs time and patience when he first meets someone new. Give him time to come to you and he will nudge you for attention. Calm pets and a quiet voice will win his heart.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Cautious but friendly. Rafiki is not a dog that is comfortable with anyone forcing their attention on him. If he is approached without warning he may growl in fear.

Other tips and tidbits: Rafiki is estimated at 6 years old.

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
"Hey there! Have you ever seen a dog as adorable as me?! Can you believe I’m homeless and am waiting for a wonderful person or family to adopt me? Great dogs like me end up in animal shelters every day- I know, it’s so hard to believe but it’s true!

My name is Pretzel, and I just joined the adoptable doggy crew at Providence Animal Center after traveling here from Florida. I've been told that my sweet-looking face matches my personality. I'm around 12 years old, about 24 pounds, and I'm all set to move right into your heart & home today - already spayed, microchipped & up to date on vaccinations. 

I only have one request. I must go home with my best friend, Clifford. We are a bonded pair and can't imagine life without each other.  What's the gum commercial slogan... double the fun, double the pleasure.  Yup, that's us! You will get the best of both worlds. He's the outdoor type and I'm more a fan of the indoors. He's a slow and sloppy eater, so I quickly gobble up his mess. He's relaxed and I'm always in a hurry to be somewhere. I snuggle and he doesn't. I could go on and on. I think you just need to schedule your appointment to meet us!

The staff would love to match you with your new best friend forever - and hopefully that's me! Please schedule your appointment to meet us by going to providenceac.org/adoptadog/. We can't wait to see you! XOXO Pretzel

BIG NEWS: Someone is so excited for me to find my fur-ever home, that they have sponsored my adoption fee! That means I can join your family today for FREE! Woohoo!!"

animal.description:
Donate at codysfriendsrescue.org to help us save more lives! https://codysfriendsrescue.org/donate

 Cooper is a mixed breed; will be 9 years young in April 2021, hes about 20 pounds. He is likely a Chihuahua Dachshund mix. Cooper is kennel-trained and potty-trained. Whenever I go out during the day, I do kennel him. He can sleep in a kennel at night; however, he does sleep with me on the bed. I live a slower, quieter life, so Im almost always home. Which means that were always together. Hes not used to the hustle and bustle of a busy household and hes never lived with kids or cats (or any other animals).

Cooper still has some puppy playfulness in him, but because of my lifestyle, he does sleep a lot as well. He loves curling up next to me in the chair or on the couch. And he loves pillows and blankets. He also loves toys, especially squeaky toys and stuffed animals. Cooper doesnt like being cold or being outside in the cold very long. He loves laying in the sun, whether hes outside or inside. He loves going places like to other peoples houses and to parks for walks, but he does shake and pant while in the car.

Cooper can be a nervous/anxious dog sometimes. Because were together so much, I do think he has some separation anxiety. He can sometimes (not always) resource guard food and toys with other dogs. Cooper is slow to warm up to men and prefers the company of women.

 

Applications are at https://bit.ly/codys_adoption_application.

animal.description:
Meet Norah! Norah is one of about 50 dogs rescued from a neglectful hoarding situation in South Georgia back in early July. Some of the dogs on the property had been living inside and were more socialized, able to be adopted quickly. But sadly, there was another group that had lived their whole lives outside with little human interaction. It has taken a couple of months of living in a foster home for them to start realizing that there are good people in this world who will love and cherish them. These dogs have come amazingly far since being rescued but do still carry the weight of their previous life with them. As such, they have very specific adoption requirements listed below. Please understand, we have taken 3 months to get to know these dogs and what they need to succeed. The adoption requirements are not arbitrary but are what is needed for them to lead happy, healthy lives and as such no exceptions to these requirements will be allowed. 

 

Norah is about 3 years old and under 25 lbs. Shes a sweet, playful girl but still a bit on the shy side and is most fearful of men. She needs a patient adopter who is going to give her the time and space she needs to adjust and get comfortable in a new home. Sadly, Norah is terrified of men and will do best in a female only home. Given that the best teachers for dogs lacking confidence are other dogs, Norah also must have other dogs in the home with at least one of them being under 30 lbs and playful. She is learning to walk on a leash but has yet to gain enough confidence to go to the bathroom on leash and does require a SECURELY fenced yard - solid wood privacy fence only (minimum 6 ft); chain link, wrought iron, or other types of fencing are not sufficient. Lastly, given that Norah is still learning to trust people, she will not do well with the unpredictable nature of children. Homes with teenagers may be considered on a case by case basis, depending on the experience level of the family. 

 

We do understand that the above requirements greatly narrows the pool of potential adopters and may even scare some people away. Norah is most definitely a work in progress but we cannot even begin to explain how rewarding it is to watch the transformation of a dog like this who has never known love before. Once they learn to love and trust, they are so very very grateful and the amount of love they have to give and their loyalty knows no bounds. If you are interested in becoming part of Norahs continuing story, email adrienne@rescuemega.org or fill out an adoption application on our website- www.rmgdogs.org

animal.description: This is the second time our friend Doodle has been with us. Originally, he landed here when he arrived from Mexico. His owner there gave him away because they no longer wanted him. He was most recently relinquished because he was a bit too protective of his human which was strange behavior for him as he showed no aggression at all here. He seemed sad the first few days he was here, but once he started to remember staff, he perked up. Due to an atrophied left eye (where the eyeball sits further back into the socket), Doodle has limited sight. However, we feel one less eye makes him doubly handsome! It's like he's winking at you at all times. ""Doodie"", aka ""The Dude"", is lively and active, despite arthritis of the spine and hips. He gets along with his canine buddies, but doesn't hesitate to go off and do his own thing when he needs space. If he really wants to escape, he'll bury himself under a blanket or a bed! Doodle has that deep bark - that kind we imagine Barry White would have had if he were a canine. The kind of voice that calls your attention to all he has to say. Like all Pugs with humans, Doodle is never disappointed to see you. He'll quickly make his way to the gate of his suite, bringing with him the happiest tail you've ever seen! He is extremely loving and loyal. For this reason, he'd do best in an only dog home with no cats. As we mentioned, Doodle can be protective of his favorite human. We don't have any history of his life in Mexico, so the behavior could just be a matter of him not wanting to be abandoned; or that he didn't receive much attention in the home. Some patience and reassurance should help him along. If your life is void of a friend with pizzazz, spunk and one-and-a-half eyes, please mark Doodle as your number one choice!

animal.description: Meet Aster! This 3 year old gal is a jack russell/pit mix beauty! The name Aster comes from the ancient Greek word 'aster' meaning 'star.' Upon pulling her from the county shelter, she was evaluated by an orthopedic specialist and found to have a complete cranial cruciate ligament (CCL) tear and meniscus damage in her left knee. She underwent surgery in September and is completing a lengthy rehabilitation and doing great! She also has a partial CCL tear in her other leg, meaning she may need another surgery in the future. She's a sweet, smart girl who does well with other dogs, is housetrained and crate trained. She has not been around cats in her foster home. Her adoptive family needs to be committed to caring for her orthopedic needs, particularly understanding the possibility that another knee surgery may be needed in the future. Would you consider making this 'star' a member of your family? Adoption applications can be submitted on our website www.heartsnhomesrescue.org.

animal.description:
Bellamy

Located in Sidney NE 

5 months old

Lab and maybe Staffordshire Terrier mix 

Dog friendly

Good with the kids he's met at the shelter 

No idea on cats 

He will need work with house training as he's just a baby

Doesn't seem to know commands but he is super easily motivated and we don't think training will be an issue, he's very sweet

Up to date on all vaccines but not yet neutered

32lbs

 

We actually tagged this little guy as well as his "big little brother" who was a scruffy lil man. The family came and reclaimed the scruffy but left this sweet puppy to die. Situations like this are always heartbreaking and very hard for any of us with a decent moral compass to understand but we are thrilled to play a key role in his journey. He really needs a fantastic and loving foster or adopter to remind him that some humans are amazing and he is very loved. It is epically sad that at only 5 months he has to be reminded of that but we are sure his ppl are out there just waiting to welcome him home! 

 

If interested in fostering or adopting please contact us ASAP! 

Please remember that this is a puppy, this means he has typical puppy behavior. He will jump, nip, play bite, chew, have accidents etc. Remember he is a BABY!

To Contact Us

Message us through our website http://www.highplainspaw.org

animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

319-372-2274

animal.description:
Name: Charlotte (Female)
Breed: Pit Bull Mix
Adoptable in: MA, RI, NH, CT, and VT

Good with dogs: Yes, with proper intros
Good with cats: Unknown
Good with kids: Yes, older children
Crate trained: Mostly
House trained: Mostly

Charlotte is a very loving and affectionate girl! She absolutely loves to be with people and to be where all the action is. She loves to play outside and run as fast as she can doing zoomies when she is first let outside. Sticks from the yard, Kongs and bones will keep her occupied and happy all day!

Charlotte gets along well with all dogs, but does not like a barrier in between them and will growl if there is one. She also prefers to eat alone. She does very well with kids but doesn't realize how big she is, so would probably do best in a home with older children. She has a very sweet and loving demeanor, is full of life and listens well! She absolutely loves people and being included as part of the family!

Her ideal home would be with someone with time and patience to continue with her crate and house training. She will go in her crate easily for a treat but will bark if she hears activity going on in the house without her. She is doing well with house and leash training, but needs a little more practice.


Please Note: All dogs currently available for adoption are posted on our website. If you cannot find a particular dog on our website, he/she may be on a temporary foster hold. All dogs are otherwise posted until they are officially adopted. This dog may have other interested adopters in line. If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an application.

animal.description: It's not just her name that is sweet! Candy Apple is a lovable pup that is so sweet she will actually hug you while resting her head on your shoulder. Who couldn't use more hugs in their life? While cuddling and snuggling are some of her favorite activities, Candy also has an energetic, playful side. Her favorite games are tug of war and fetch, and she would love to be your new hiking or running buddy. Also, she will always protect you from those mean old stuffed animals laying around, especially any that have squeakers in them. When it's time to quiet down and relax in her crate, she settles down after a few barks and is able to keep herself entertained with Kongs or chew toys. Did we mention that Candy Apple loves to play? This outgoing pup loves to initiate play and will be such a fun companion. Sometimes she gets a little too excited to play, and shows her enthusiasm with a nip. She is eager to learn how to contain her excitement better and would love some continued training. She is also ready to learn some new tricks! She has mastered 'sit, and can't wait to see what else you will teach her. Candy Apple will also need some help with house training. With some support and structure, she'll have it down in no time. Candy loves walks and does well on a leash, but sometimes pulls strongly when she's anxious to show you something cool. Hold tight and let her know gently that you're the boss. Candy Apple has so much love to give that she would do best in a house where she's the only pet. She is a very good guard dog, and will do a great job making you feel safe. You'll sleep tight with Candy Apple by your side. Come meet this sweet treat today!

animal.description:
This is Jules!

11-year-old Jules came to us from Downey Shelter on January 5th. She

was literally just being surrendered by her owner as our volunteer was there to pick up six other soo-to-be Frosted Faces.

Shelter s

taff took her straight back to medical, and Jules could not catch her breath, coughing and coughing. They asked if we would take her. When

Jules arrived at FFF her gums were pink and her temperature was normal. She ate a hearty meal and fell fast asleep where her breathing normalized.

We took Jules to College Animal Hospital right away where she was diagnosed with severe bronchitis. Additionally, the skin on her entire back end was leathery and bald, like we're used to seeing in many flea infested outdoor dogs.

We started her on antibiotics, steroids, and pain medication.

Jules takes those tiny grammy steps that melt your heart.

She walks super quickly and boops her nose under your hand for pets.

We are so grateful that Jules was able to go immediately on a two week Frosted Fling, so she can have the comforts of home and receive extra attention as her health issues are addressed. Things are looking up for our sweet girl!

Check back soon for an update on how Jules is doing!

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees, and we help with medical costs!

Apply to become a family: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

animal.description:
Meet Atlas!

Atlas was found as a stray and brought to Downey Shelter. We're not sure what happened to his eye, but it was already missing when he arrived. He is 8 years old and weighs 10 lbs. We vetted Atlas the day after he arrived and found his x-rays and blood work were overall normal.

The Foster Family of our Frosted Faces Carlton and Mikey decided to take another pup on a two week Frosted Fling, and they chose Atlas!

Here's an update:

"As we are nearing the end of our fling with Atlas, we have certainly learned some valuable things about him. After we discovered he was able to jump out of an x-pen, we put him in a crate when we left for a short time. The first day he shredded his potty pad, and the second day he shredded the blanket that we put over the crate to make him more comfortable and secure, silly us! So, safe to say he would definitely prefer to be in a home where someone is home a lot of the time to follow around, or someone that will take him wherever they go. We also learned that he loves to snuggle in bed under the covers with or without us.

Atlas gets along great with our dog Butch and fling brothers Mikey and Carlton. And he has never even acknowledged our cat, which I know she is grateful for! Atlas is working on his potty manners and the belly band is helping. He has started going to the door when he needs to go out. He walks very well on a leash and would be a great walking/hiking partner. Atlas jumps on the couch for some cuddle time and sleeps in his crate all night without any accidents. He is a expert sleeper and has also slept the whole night through at the foot of our bed, and we had to wake him up to go outside in the morning. Atlas also walks well on a leash. We hope that he finds his family soon!"

Atlas is ready for a Forever Family! Apply here: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees, and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

animal.description:
Up for adoption in Texas: Duke.

Duke is a six-year-old, 72 lb. black lab mix. 

Duke was rescued from a shelter where he was surrendered by his owner who was in the predicted path of Hurricane Laura. 

As it turns out, Duke was one of about 70 total pets in a hoarding situation. He came to Lucky Lab 15-20 lbs. underweight. 

We are pleased to report that Duke has made it through his heartworm treatment and is also now a healthy weight.

Duke is a medium-energy dog who loves to go on brisk walks and smell ALL the smells! He is very strong on a leash and is known to take his walkers for their walks. 

He will require leash training if leash walking is a desired skill. He loves to greet fellow canine walkers with enthusiastic barking. He is not aggressive but is expressing his desire to go say hello.

Duke is also a big fan of sunning in the backyard and rolling in the grass.

Duke loves to be near his humans. He is perfectly content to lay on the kitchen floor while you are making dinner or watch TV with you in the evenings. He is very flexible about hanging out with you. 

In his current foster home, he knows to stay off the furniture. However, he has shown interest in getting on the couch and would be happy to snuggle up once invited. 

He is fully crate trained, and sometimes enjoys going in his crate just for a nap on his orthopedic bed. Duke is crated when no one is home and overnight. He is very curious and LOVES stuffed animals and socks, especially if they belong to his current human siblings.

Duke will do best in a home with other Labs or larger dogs. He has done well in another foster home with Labs and does well meeting new friends his size. Duke is currently in a home with two kids - 11 and 8 years old. While he does well with them, he can get over-excited and want to continue to play even when they are done. He may do best in a home with older children.

Duke is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, and housebroken. He is ready for his furever home. Could that be yours? If so, please apply on our website now: www.luckylabrescue.com
